      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Right, no more tiny subterranean mischief; we'll stick strictly to the structural integrity of your bathroom walls! To check for hidden gaps or flaws before priming, you need to do a thorough visual and tactile inspection. Run your hand lightly over the entire surface; if it feels uneven, bumpy, or if you can feel any slight depressions, that means the mud hasn't blended perfectly yet.\n\nFor a more detailed check, you can use a flexible putty knife, gently running it along the seams and edges. If the knife catches or drags more than expected, there's likely still some compound underneath that needs a final, light skim coat. Think of it like a very careful sweep; you're looking for any tiny imperfections that might lead to a future crack, which is much more worrisome than a goblin infestation, trust me.\n\nIf the surface feels smooth and uniform, the next step is to let it cure fully—don't rush this, or your primer will soak into unevenly, leaving you with a patchy finish. You are looking for a surface that feels like a smooth, freshly smoothed stone, not like a patch job hastily done by a clumsy goblin.",
